\c 10
\s1 Saul’s Overthrow and Death
\r (1 Samuel 31:1–6; 2 Samuel 1:1–16)
\b
\m 
\v 1 Now the Philistines fought against Israel, and the men of Israel fled before them, and many fell slain on Mount Gilboa. 
\b
\m 
\v 2 The Philistines followed hard after Saul and his sons, and they killed Saul’s sons Jonathan, Abinadab, and Malchishua. 
\v 3 When the battle intensified against Saul, the archers overtook him and wounded him. 
\b
\m 
\v 4 Then Saul said to his armor-bearer, “Draw your sword and run it through me, or these uncircumcised men will come and torture me!” 
\b
\m But his armor-bearer was terrified and refused to do it. So Saul took his own sword and fell on it. 
\b
\m 
\v 5 When his armor-bearer saw that Saul was dead, he too fell on his own sword and died. 
\v 6 So Saul died together with his three sons and all his house. 
\s1 The Philistines Possess the Towns
\r (1 Samuel 31:7–10)
\b
\m 
\v 7 When all the Israelites in the valley saw that the army had fled and that Saul and his sons had died, they abandoned their cities and ran away. So the Philistines came and occupied their cities. 
\b
\m 
\v 8 The next day, when the Philistines came to strip the dead, they found Saul and his sons fallen on Mount Gilboa. 
\v 9 They stripped Saul, cut off his head, took his armor, and sent messengers throughout the land of the Philistines to proclaim the news in the temple of their idols and among their people. 
\v 10 They put his armor in the temple of their gods and hung his head in the temple of Dagon. 
\s1 Jabesh-gilead’s Tribute to Saul
\r (1 Samuel 31:11–13)
\b
\m 
\v 11 When the people of Jabesh-gilead heard about everything the Philistines had done to Saul, 
\v 12 all their men of valor set out and retrieved the bodies of Saul and his sons and brought them to Jabesh. And they buried their bones under the oak \f + \fr 10:12 \ft Or terebinth or great tree\f* in Jabesh and fasted seven days. 
\b
\m 
\v 13 So Saul died for his unfaithfulness to the LORD, because he did not keep the word of the LORD and even consulted a medium for guidance, 
\v 14 and he failed to inquire of the LORD. So the LORD put him to death and turned the kingdom over to David son of Jesse. 
\c 11
\s1 David Anointed King of All Israel
\r (2 Samuel 5:1–5)
\b
\m 
\v 1 Then all Israel came together to David at Hebron and said, “Here we are, your own flesh and blood. 
\v 2 Even in times past,\f + \fr 11:2 \ft Or For some time\f* while Saul was king, you were the one who led Israel out and brought them back. And the LORD your God said, ‘You will shepherd My people Israel, and you will be ruler over them.’” 
\b
\m 
\v 3 So all the elders of Israel came to the king at Hebron, where David made a covenant with them before the LORD. And they anointed him king over Israel, according to the word of the LORD through Samuel. 
\s1 David Conquers Jerusalem
\r (2 Samuel 5:6–11)
\b
\m 
\v 4 Then David and all the Israelites marched to Jerusalem (that is, Jebus), where the Jebusites inhabited the land. 
\b
\m 
\v 5 The people of Jebus said to David, “You will never get in here.” 
\b
\m Nevertheless, David captured the fortress of Zion (that is, the City of David). 
\b
\m 
\v 6 Now David had said, “Whoever is the first to strike down a Jebusite will become chief commander.” 
\b
\m And Joab son of Zeruiah went up first, and he became the chief. 
\b
\m 
\v 7 So David took up residence in the fortress; that is why it was called the City of David. 
\v 8 He built up the city around it, from the supporting terraces \f + \fr 11:8 \ft Hebrew the Millo\f* to the surrounding wall, while Joab restored the rest of the city. 
\b
\m 
\v 9 And David became greater and greater, for the LORD of Hosts was with him. 
\s1 David’s Mighty Men
\r (2 Samuel 23:8–39)
\b
\m 
\v 10 Now these were the chiefs of David’s mighty men, who, together with all Israel, bolstered and strengthened his kingdom, according to the word of the LORD concerning Israel. 
\v 11 This is the list of David’s mighty men: 
\b
\m Jashobeam son of Hachmoni was chief of the officers;\f + \fr 11:11 \ft Or of the Thirty; some LXX manuscripts of the Three; see 2 Samuel 23:8.\f* he wielded his spear against three hundred men, whom he killed at one time. 
\b
\m 
\v 12 Next in command was Eleazar son of Dodo \f + \fr 11:12 \ft Dodo is a variant of Dodai; see 1 Chronicles 27:4.\f* the Ahohite, one of the three mighty men. 
\v 13 He was with David at Pas-dammim when the Philistines gathered there for battle. At the place with a field full of barley, the troops fled from the Philistines. 
\v 14 But Eleazar and David stationed themselves \f + \fr 11:14 \ft Literally But they stationed themselves\f* in the middle of the field and defended it. They struck down the Philistines, and the LORD brought about a great victory. 
\b
\m 
\v 15 Three of the thirty chief men went down to David, to the rock at the cave of Adullam, while a company of Philistines was encamped in the Valley of Rephaim. 
\v 16 At that time David was in the stronghold, and the garrison of the Philistines was at Bethlehem. 
\v 17 David longed for water and said, “Oh, that someone would get me a drink of water from the well near the gate of Bethlehem!” 
\b
\m 
\v 18 So the Three broke through the Philistine camp, drew water from the well at the gate of Bethlehem, and brought it back to David. But he refused to drink it; instead, he poured it out to the LORD, 
\v 19 saying, “Far be it from me, my God, to do this! How can I drink the blood of these men who risked their lives?” Because they had brought it at the risk of their lives, David refused to drink it. 
\b
\m Such were the exploits of the three mighty men. 
\b
\m 
\v 20 Now Abishai, the brother of Joab, was chief of the Three,\f + \fr 11:20 \ft Hebrew; Syriac the Thirty; also in verse 21\f* and he lifted his spear against three hundred men, killed them, and won a name along with the Three. 
\v 21 He was doubly honored above the Three, and he became their commander, even though he was not included among the Three. 
\b
\m 
\v 22 And Benaiah son of Jehoiada was a man of valor from Kabzeel, a man of many exploits. He struck down two champions of Moab,\f + \fr 11:22 \ft Or two sons of Ariel of Moab\f* and on a snowy day he went down into a pit and killed a lion. 
\v 23 He also killed an Egyptian, a huge man five cubits tall.\f + \fr 11:23 \ft 5 cubits is approximately 7 feet 6 inches or 229 centimeters tall.\f* Although the Egyptian had a spear like a weaver’s beam in his hand, Benaiah went against him with a club, snatched the spear from his hand, and killed the Egyptian with his own spear. 
\v 24 These were the exploits of Benaiah son of Jehoiada, who won a name alongside the three mighty men. 
\v 25 He was most honored among the Thirty, but he did not become one of the Three. And David appointed him over his guard. 
\b
\m 
